06037nam a22008775i 9781400821334DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t19941994nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008213347 a10.1515/97814008213342doi  a(DE-B1597)446084  a(OCoLC)979754366  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDK222.C85 1994 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a305.5630947a306.4/094700aCultures in Flux :bLower-Class Values, Practices, and Resistance in Late Imperial Russia /ced. by Stephen P. Frank, Mark D. Steinberg.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Death Ritual among Russian and Ukrainian Peasants: Linkages between the Living and the Dead -- t2. Women, Men, and the Languages of Peasant Resistance, 1870–1907 -- t3. Peasant Popular Culture and the Origins of Soviet Authoritarianism -- t4. Confronting the Domestic Other: Rural Popular Culture and Its Enemies in Fin-de-Siècle Russia -- t5. Death of the Folk Song? -- t6. Shows for the People: Public Amusement Parks in Nineteenth-Century St. Petersburg -- t7. For Tsar and Fatherland? Russian Popular Culture and the First World War -- t8. The Penny Press and Its Readers -- t9. Worker-Authors and the Cult of the Person -- t10. Culture Besieged: Hooliganism and Futurism -- tSELECT BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe popular culture of urban and rural tsarist Russia revealed a dynamic and troubled world. Stephen Frank and Mark Steinberg have gathered here a diverse collection of essays by Western and Russian scholars who question conventional interpretations and recall neglected stories about popular behavior, politics, and culture. What emerges is a new picture of lower-class life, in which traditions and innovations intermingled and social boundaries and identities were battered and reconstructed. The authors vividly convey the vitality as well as the contradictions of social life in old regime Russia, while also confronting problems of interpretation, methodology, and cultural theory. They tell of peasant death rites and religious beliefs, family relationships and brutalities, defiant peasant women, folk songs, urban amusement parks, expressions of popular patriotism, the penny press, workers' notions of the self, street hooliganism, and attempts by educated Russians to transform popular festivities. Together, the authors portray popular culture not as a static, separate world, but as the dynamic means through which lower-class Russians engaged the world around them. In addition to the editors, the contributors to this volume are Daniel R. Brower, Barbara Alpern Engel, Hubertus F. Jahn, Al'bin M. Konechnyi, Boris N. Mironov, Joan Neuberger, Robert A. Rothstein, and Christine D. Worobec.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFolklorexRussia. 0aFolklorezRussia. 0aPeasantsxRussia. 0aPeasantszRussia. 0aPopular culturexHistoryx19th centuryxRussia. 0aPopular culturezRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classxRussia. 0aWorking classzRussia. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aBrower, Daniel R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngel, Barbara Alpern, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Stephen P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Stephen P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJahn, Hubertus F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonechnyi, Al’bin M., econtribut